ries of colonial rulers. Today’s youth remain at the bottom of the fiercely hierarchical and polarized societies of the Grassfields, and it is their response to centuries of exploitation that Nicolas Argenti takes up in this absorbing and original book. Beginning his study with a political analysis of youth in the Grassfields from the eighteenth century to the present, Argenti pays special attention to the repeated violent revolts staged by young victims of political oppression. He then combines this history with extensive ethnographic fieldwork in the Oku chiefdom, discovering that the specter of past violence lives on in the masked dance performances that have earned intense devotion from today’s youth. Argenti contends that by evoking the imagery of past cataclysmic events, these masquerades allow young Oku men and women to address the inequities they face in their relations with elders and state authorities today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHistory. 0aMarginality, SocialxHistoryxCameroonxNorth-West Province. 0aMarginality, SocialzCameroonzNorth-West ProvincexHistory. 0aMarginality, Social. 0aOku (African people)xHistory. 0aOku (African people)xPolitics and government. 0aOku (African people)xSocial life and customs. 0aOku (African people). 0aSlaveryxHistoryxCameroonxNorth-West Province. 0aSlaveryzCameroonzNorth-West ProvincexHistory. 0aSlavery. 0aSocial sciences. 0aYoung menxAttitudesxCameroonxNorth-West Province. 0aYoung menxPsychologyxCameroonxNorth-West Province. 0aYoung menzCameroonzNorth-West ProvincexAttitudes. 0aYoung menzCameroonzNorth-West ProvincexPsychology. 0aYoung men. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acameroon grassfields, youth, africa, violence, marginalization, slavery, forced labor, colonialism, exploitation, revolt, revolution